label.value: abnormal mitotic spindle pole body insertion into nuclear envelope, with spindle pole body in cytoplasm

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the insertion of a spindle pole body (SPB) into the nuclear envelope is abnormal, and the SPB enters the cytoplasm. An open fenestra remains present in the nuclear envelope.

label.value: normal attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochore

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the attachment of spindle microtubules to the kinetochore during a mitotic or meiotic nuclear division is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: decreased histone H3-K9 methylation at silent mating-type cassette during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which methylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 in heterochromatin at the silenced mating-type cassettes occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: decreased histone H3-K9 methylation at subtelomeric heterochromatin during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which methylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 in heterochromatin at subtelomeric regions occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: decreased protein localization to heterochromatin at silent mating-type cassette

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to heterochromatin at the silenced mating-type cassettes is decreased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal histone H3-K14 acetylation at centromere outer repeat during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which acetylation of lysine at position 14 of histone H3 in centromere outer repeat regions is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal histone H3-K9 acetylation at centromere outer repeat during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which acetylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 in centromere outer repeat regions is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal protein localization to subtelomeric heterochromatin

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to heterochromatin in subtelomeric regions is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished plasma membrane to vacuole transport after nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the transport of a substance from the plasma membrane to the vacuole does not occur when the cell is subject to, or recovering from, nitrogen starvation. Transport normally occurs in two stages, plasma membrane to endosome followed by endosome to vacuole transport.

definition.value: This term can be used to annotate phenotypes in which a protein that normally appears at the plasma membrane transiently during nitrogen starvation is not subsequently transported to the vacuole. It can also be used for the movement of other substances (e.g. lipids or ions) to or from the vacuole. If it is used for a protein transport phenotype, we recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which vacuolar transport is abnormal.

definition.value: This term can be used for protein transport or for the movement of other substances (e.g. lipids or ions) to or from the vacuole. If it is used for a protein transport phenotype, we recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay.

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of RNA measured in a cell during one or both meiotic nuclear divisions is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Total RNA or a specific RNA, such as the mRNA transcribed from a gene of interest, may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased number of Sad1 foci during response to DNA damage

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of sites at which the protein Sad1 accumulates is greater than normal during a cellular response to DNA damage.

definition.value: Sad1 is normally located at the spindle pole body, but during a response to DNA damage, Sad1 foci associated with double-strand breaks appear.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of sites at which the protein Kms1 accumulates is greater than normal.

label.value: increased number of Kms1 foci during response to DNA damage

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of sites at which the protein Kms1 accumulates is greater than normal during a cellular response to DNA damage.

label.value: increased rate of Sad1 focus formation during response to DNA damage

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the rate, or speed, of formation of foci containing the protein Sad1 is increased during a cellular response to DNA damage.

label.value: increased double-strand break repair via nonhomologous end joining

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of double-strand break repair via nonhomologous end joining (NHEJ) is increased. NHEJ is the repair of double-strand breaks in DNA in which the two broken ends are rejoined with little or no sequence complementarity.

label.value: decreased anaphase-promoting complex-dependent protein catabolic process

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of ubiquitin-dependent protein degradation with ubiquitin-protein ligation catalyzed by the anaphase-promoting complex, and mediated by the proteasome, is decreased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which replication fork processing is abnormal. Replication fork processing is process in which a DNA replication fork that has stalled (due to DNA damage, DNA secondary structure, bound proteins, dNTP shortage, or other causes) is repaired and replication is restarted.

label.value: loss of gross chromosomal rearrangement during replication fork processing

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the increase in gross chromosomal rearrangements that normally results from processing arrested replication forks is diminished or abolished.

label.value: increased gross chromosomal rearrangement during replication fork processing

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the increase in gross chromosomal rearrangements that normally results from processing arrested replication forks is enhanced, i.e. the incidence of rearrangement increases more than in wild type when an arrested fork is processed.

label.value: decreased replication slippage during replication fork processing

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the increase in small deletions or duplications ("replication slippage") that normally results from processing arrested replication forks is diminished or abolished.
A cell phenotype in which vacuoles are smaller than normal during sporulation.

A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to a protein complex is abnormal. The protein whose binding to the protein complex is affected may be encoded by the mutated gene, or may be encoded by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can be used for any interaction with a protein complex that is affected by a mutation, whether or not the mutated gene product is one of the interacting proteins. We recommend noting which proteins were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to the anaphase-promoting complex (APC) occurs to a greater extent than normal. The protein whose binding to the APC may be encoded by the mutated gene, or may be encoded by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can be used for any interaction with the APC that is affected by a mutation, whether or not the mutated gene product is one of the interacting proteins. We recommend noting which proteins were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished anaphase-promoting complex-dependent protein catabolic process

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of ubiquitin-dependent protein degradation with ubiquitin-protein ligation catalyzed by the anaphase-promoting complex, and mediated by the proteasome, is abolished.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal anaphase-promoting complex-dependent protein catabolic process

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of ubiquitin-dependent protein degradation with ubiquitin-protein ligation catalyzed by the anaphase-promoting complex, and mediated by the proteasome, is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a single cell grows in a shape that consists of two curves in opposite directions.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which formation of the mature 3' end of an snRNA molecule is abnormal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which formation of the mature 3' end of an snRNA molecule is abolished.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which formation of the mature 3' end of an snRNA molecule is decreased.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which formation of the mature 3' end of an snRNA molecule is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of any rRNA precursor measured in a cell is higher than normal.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of any rRNA precursor measured in a cell is lower than normal.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of mRNA splicing via the spliceosome is abolished.
A cellular process phenotype in which the first meiotic nuclear division is abnormal.

label.value: decreased duration of meiotic prophase I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the duration of prophase of the first meiotic nuclear division is shorter than normal.
A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the mitotic or meiotic spindle is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of dehydrodolichyl diphosphate synthase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of dehydrodolichyl diphosphate synthase activity is decreased.

label.value: branched, elongated cell with branch forming adjacent to septum

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is elongated and a branch forms adjacent to an existing septum.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'viable cell population' (FYPO:0002058) or one of its descendants.

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during one or both meiotic nuclear divisions is higher than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which cells in a population of spores are viable.

label.value: normal meiotic sister chromatid cohesion during meiotic prophase I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cohesion between sister chromatids is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during prophase of the first meiotic nuclear division.

label.value: meiotic spindle absent from cell during meiosis II

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the cell does not contain a detectable meiotic spindle during the second meiotic nuclear division.

label.value: decreased meiotic DNA double-strand break formation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which generation of double-strand breaks at defined hotspots throughout the genome during meiosis I is decreased.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to fluphenazine. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of fluphenazine that allows wild type cells to grow.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to cytochalasin D. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of cytochalasin D that allows wild type cells to grow.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing aculeacin A.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mRNA splicing via the spliceosome is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of any unspliced or incompletely spliced mRNA precursor measured in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.
